Predicting 3 km Running Times based on laboratory testing.

Study Description:

Sixteen male well-trained middle and long distance runners performed a 3 km time trial and a number of running tests in the laboratory including their running velocity (km.h-1) at a blood lactate concentration of 4 mmol.l-1 (v4mM) and at their Lactate Threshold (vTlac). All the laboratory testing took place on a motorised treadmill while distance running performance was determined by 3 km time trials on an indoor 200m track.

Aims:

To investigate whether there is sufficient evidence of a dependency of 3 km running time on v-4mM in the population of male runners of interest in order to use their blood lactate markers (i.e. v4mM) to predict their 3km running time (i.e. Running.Time).

Response Variable: 3km running time (Running.Time) Explanatory Variable: blood lactate markers (v4mM)

From assessing the summary statistics for the data there are are a few key items of interest. The running time column has a relatively small range and deviation. The maximum and minimum time is less than 3 units, and it has a standard deviation of just 0.7442. Following the previous point, it also has a relatively tight Inter-quartile Range between a 1stQu of 9.090 and a 3rdQu of 10.1. This may suggest a lot of players performed similarly for the 3Km run.

For the Blood lactate concentration (v4mM) it has a mean of 17.068 milimoles and a standard deviation of 1.848.

The max and min of our explanatory variable is also worth noting. With linear models it is bad practice to use input values outside of the range of the explanatory variable. For example, you can’t predict the Running.Time given a v4mM above 20.40 or below 14.20.

Scatterplot

Task: Generate the scatterplot of v4mM vs Running.Time and interpret it.

ggplot(running, aes(x=v4mM, y=Running.Time)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Blood Lactate Concentration (4mmol)", y = "3km Running Time", 
       title = "Scatterplot of 3km Running Time and Blood Lactate Concentration")

Each point on the scatter plot is one of the players who took part in the test. The scatter plot reveals that the 3km running time is negatively correlated with Blood Lactate Concentration, i.e the higher the levels of Blood Lactate Concentration v4mM a player has, the faster they will be at running the 3km. This means that the the players who have lower levels of Blood Lactate Concentration (v4mM) generally have faster 3km running times than those players who have high levels of v4mM.

There does seem to be some spread around the middle of the data between 9.0 and 9.5 Running.Time. There is one player above and one player below the trend in the data. Within that time threshold there also seems to be some what of a cluster of similar results. The reason for that slight clustering should be investigated further.

Fitting a Simple Linear Regression Model

Task: Fit a simple linear regression model to assess the dependence of 3 km running time on v-4mM in the population of male runners.

running.model = lm(Running.Time ~ v4mM, running)
running.model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Running.Time ~ v4mM, data = running)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)         v4mM  
##     15.8223      -0.3729

Equation of line of best fit

Task: Write down the equation of the line of best fit and also provide an interpretation of the slope and intercept of the corresponding line of best fit. Justify if the intercept is or is not a useful quantity in this application.

\[\text{3km Running Time} = 15.8223 + -0.3729(\text{ Blood Lactate Concentration }) + \epsilon_i\] The slope \(\beta_1\) is -0.3729. This means that the slope is at a somewhat negative downward slope. It is ‘somewhat’ negative because the absolute value 0.3729 is relatively low, and it is downward sloping because the sign (-) is negative. In terms of the data, it means that for every unit increase of a players 3km running time, the amount of Blood Lactate Concentration goes down by -0.3729.

b0 is intercept The intercept \(\beta_0\) is 15.8223. This means that the line of best fit cuts the \(Y\) axis when \(X\) = 0. In terms of the dataset, this means that the Running.Time value would be 15.8223 when blood lactate concentration in 0. This intercept is not really useful in terms this application as it is impossible or highly irregular to have a blood lactate concentration of 0 as it is a natural feature of human biology. A report from University of California Davis on blood lactate states…

“The concentration of blood lactate is usually 1-2 mmol/L at rest…” source

Make some predictions

Task: Predict the running time (i.e. Running.Time) when the blood lactate markers (i.e. v4mM) are 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 and 20 mmol.l-1. For each of the predictions produce the confidence intervals and prediction intervals and interpret the results carefully.

v4mM.14to20 = data.frame(
  v4mM = c(14:20)
)
predict(running.model, newdata = v4mM.14to20, interval = "confidence")

## 7  8.365197  8.065626  8.664767

Predicting the Confidence interval with the running.model gives us 3 columns, fit, lwr, and upr. The confidence interval reflects uncertainty around mean prediction values. Fit is the regular line of best fit for the input datapoints in the dataframe v4mM.14to20, this is the same line as we saw earlier in the ‘Line of Best Fit’ plot. Each of the 7 rows in the returned dataframe is one of the values we passed in as part of the v4mM.14to20 dataframe.

The lwr and upr confidence columns show the upper and lower confidence limits for the expected values with 95% confidence. 95% of the data is expected to lie between the lwr and upr values for each data point.

predict(running.model, newdata = v4mM.14to20, interval = "prediction")
##         fit      lwr       upr
## 1 10.602320 9.905285 11.299356
## 2 10.229467 9.561059 10.897874
## 3  9.856613 9.206309 10.506916
## 4  9.483759 8.840144 10.127373
## 5  9.110905 8.462212  9.759598
## 6  8.738051 8.072781  9.403320
## 7  8.365197 7.672678  9.057715

The prediction interval gives uncertainty around a single value. For our prediction interval it means that 95% of the players with a v4mM of 14 will have a 3km Run performance between 9.905 and 11.2999.

Plots with prediction intervals

Task: Add the produced confidence and prediction intervals to the scatter plot with the line of best fit and interpret it.

pred.int = predict(running.model, newdata = running, interval = "prediction")

running.df2 = cbind(running, pred.int) # store predictions alongside original dataset

ggplot(running.df2, aes(y = Running.Time, x = v4mM)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = lm) +
  geom_line(aes(y = lwr), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") + # 3. Add prediction intervals
  geom_line(aes(y = upr), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +

       title = "Scatterplot with line of best fit and prediction intervals")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The confidence interval is the gray areas either side of the line of best fit (blue). The red dashed lines from pred.int above and below the line of best fit are the upr and lwr bounds of the prediction interval. The bounds of the confidence interval are significantly tighter than the one for the prediction interval but that is to be expected.

All of the data points lie within the bounds of the prediction interval, with the one outlier value we made note of in the EDA phase being the only point on the edge.

More prediction

Task: Predict the running time (i.e. Running.Time) when the blood lactate markers (i.e. v4mM) are 18.9 mmol.l-1.

predict(running.model, newdata = data.frame(v4mM = 18.9))
##        1 
## 8.775336

Task: Why is the result here is different from 8.82, the value in the heading of the data presented above. i.e. the running time when the blood lactate markers (i.e. v4mM) are 18.9 mmol.l-1?

The values are similar but different because the value 8.775336 is based off of the line of best fit of our running.model. Unlike the linear model we have constructed, the information found in the heading of the data presented was actual test results from the study. The linear model is just a line of best fit where the sum of squared residuals is lowest, and is used to make inference. In this case, the inferred Running.Time was an approximation based on the existing datapoints.

Task: Predict the running time (i.e. Running.Time) when the blood lactate markers (i.e. v4mM) are 2.6 mmol.l-1. Explain if you have any concern related to this prediction?

predict(running.model, newdata = data.frame(v4mM = 2.6))
##        1 
## 14.85286
min(running$v4mM)
## [1] 14.2

There are concerns around the usefulness of this predicted value because it is generally bad practice to extrapolate beyond the range of the data. As you can see in the above cell, within our dataset of 16 players the lowest value of blood lactate concentration is 14.2. Extrapolating outside the range of the data we used to train the model as it may no longer hold true. Changing the input data will change the intercept and slope, thus changing the model.

Overall Conclusion

Task: State your overall conclusions from the modelling of the association between running time and the blood lactate marker.

I would conclude that there is sufficient evidence of a dependency of 3km running time on v-4mM in the population of male runners in the study in order to use their blood lactate markers to predict their 3km running time.

There is a clear association between the amount of v4mM in a player’s blood and their performance in the 3km run. The relationship is strongly negatively correlated, meaning that the datapoints move consistently in a downward slope as the X variable increases (Blood Lactate Concentration). The high Pearson’s correlation coefficient supports this conclusion.

The data was very plausibly linear so a Simple Linear Regression model was created. After assessing the prediction interval I conclude that the model is sufficient evidence for this to be used to predict running times. That being said I would avoid using input values outside the bounds of what the model was trained on.
